# bootstrap-sdlc — {{AGENT_NAME}}

Three sections, one per audience — read the one that applies to you: **Protocol** (main agent), **Planning Mode** (episode planner), **Evaluation Criteria** (episode evaluator). Phase is checked via `uv run python {{PROVIDER_SKILLS_DIR}}/bootstrap-sdlc/scripts/bootstrap_state.py phase`.

---

## Protocol (read by the main agent)

### Phase semantics

- `prd` — you may only produce / refine the PRD artifact. The PRD stays product-scoped (target users, problem statement, success criteria, non-goals, hard constraints) and must NOT contain architecture or technology choices.
- `design` — the PRD is locked. You may produce / refine the architecture and assumptions artifacts. You may NOT edit the PRD or write business implementation code.
- `done` — bootstrap gate is released. Normal heartbeat rules apply.

Runtime, language, and package manager are fixed by the harness (uv + Python for Claude, Node.js for Codex) — treat them as given context, not as decisions to record in either artifact. Only record technology choices the agent actually has freedom over (external libraries, storage format, API schemas, etc.).

### The three artifacts

All bootstrap output lives in exactly three files under `Memory/knowledge/conceptual/`:

- `conceptual--bootstrap--prd.md` — product spec, owned by phase `prd`
- `conceptual--bootstrap--architecture.md` — technical design (module boundaries, data flow, key interfaces, technology choices with rationale), owned by phase `design`
- `conceptual--bootstrap--assumptions.md` — every load-bearing assumption extracted from PRD + architecture, each entry tracking `status` (`unverified` / `verified`), `verification` method, `evidence` (file path, URL, or literal command output), and `verified_at`, owned by phase `design`

Each file uses the standard knowledge-note frontmatter (`name`, `description`, `kind: conceptual`). Keep them small and single-purpose; do NOT merge them.

### What you are NOT allowed to write during bootstrap

While phase is `prd` or `design`, the only files you may create or modify are:

- the three bootstrap artifacts above
- the current episode file under `Memory/episodes/YYYY/MM/`
- the mailbox (via the mailbox-operate skill)
- `Runtime/bootstrap_state.json` — and only via `bootstrap_state.py advance` / `reset`, never by hand

Any other write is forbidden and will be rejected by the evaluator.

### How to advance a phase

Phase transitions require explicit human approval via mailbox — never advance on your own judgment.

1. When the artifact(s) for the current phase look complete, send `mailbox-operate send --await-reply` to the human referencing the artifact file(s) and asking for approval to advance.
2. When the reply arrives and is unambiguous approval, run `bootstrap_state.py advance --to <next_phase> --approver human --note "approved via mail.<mailbox_id>"`. The `note` MUST cite the real mailbox_id — the evaluator cross-checks it.

### How to reset (rare, human-only)

If the human explicitly instructs you to re-bootstrap (e.g. after a major goal change), run `bootstrap_state.py reset --approver human --note "reset requested in mail.<mailbox_id>"`. Never reset on your own judgment.

